cotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Montgomery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and northern Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Sainte-Foy-de-Montgomery and Saint-Germain-de-Montgomery (Calvados). In Ireland this surname was present in the medieval period, died out, and was then reintroduced from Scotland in the 17th century. It has been Gaelicized in Ireland as <b>Mac Iomaire</b> and in Scotland as <b>Mac Gumaraid</b>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Montgomery was born in 1125, in Pembrokeshire, Wales, his father, Philip de Montgomery, was 23 and his mother, Margaret of Dunbar, was 23. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret Marjory FitzWalter. He died in 1165, in Renfrewshire, Scotland, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1125–1165":"1125–1165","1127–1200":"1127–1200","1127–Female":"1127–Surnud","1144–1221":"1144–1221","–Male":"Surnud","1102–1177":"1102–1177","1102–1154":"1102–1154","1118":"1118","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1102":"1102","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1221":"1221","1144":"1144","1154":"1154","1165":"1165","about 1144":"umbes 1144","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Angus, Scotland":"Douglas and Angus, Forfarshire, Scotland","Dunbar, East Lothian, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1125–1165":"1125–1165","1127–1200":"1127–1200","1127–Female":"1127–Kuollut","1144–1221":"1144–1221","–Male":"Kuollut","1102–1177":"1102–1177","1102–1154":"1102–1154","1118":"1118","1127":"1127","1125":"1125","1102":"1102","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1221":"1221","1144":"1144","1154":"1154","1165":"1165","about 1144":"noin 1144","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Angus, Scotland":"Douglas and Angus, Forfarshire, Scotland","Dunbar, East Lothian, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Eaglesham, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1125–1165":"1125–1165","1127–1200":"1127–1200","1127–Female":"1127–Décédée","1144–1221":"